    "John Trapp": "In order upon the wood. ] Showing that ministers must rightly divide, and dispose the word of God, { #2Ti 2:15 } and evidently set forth Christ crucified. { #Ga 3:1 }\nVer.\n8. In order upon the wood.] Showing that ministers must rightly divide, and dispose the word of God, {#2Ti 2:15} and evidently [v_Gal_3_1] set forth Christ crucified. {#Ga 3:1} [v_Heb_7_26]\nVer.\n8. He shall bring it unto the altar.] God would have all their offerings brought to one altar; both to figure out the one only all sufficient sacririce of Christ, and to teach all the faithful to consent in one and the same truth of the gospel.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 139": "Of their flesh shall ye not eat, etc.] Meaning, not of swine only,\nbut of the camel, coney, and hare:\nand their carcass shall ye not touch; which must not be understood of\ntouching them in any sense; for then it would have been unlawful for a Jew\nto have rode upon a camel, or to take out and make use of hog\u2019s lard in\nmedicine; but of touching them in order to kill them, and prepare them for\nfood, and eat them; and indeed all unnecessary touching of them is\nforbidden, lest it should bring them to the eating of them; though perhaps it\nmay chiefly respect the touching of them dead:\nthey [are] unclean to you: one and all of them; for as this was said of each\nof them in particular, so now of all of them together; and which holds good\nof all wild creatures not named, to whom the description above belongs,\nand which used to be eaten by other nations; some of which were called\nPamphagi, from eating all sorts, and others Agriophagi, from eating wild\ncreatures, as lions, panthers, elephants f249, etc.\nVer.",
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "The compilation of the traditions that now make up Genesis through Numbers is a complex his-\ntorical problem. It is usually concluded by modern interpreters that there were three prior stages of\nPentateuchal composition upon which the Priestly writers\u2019 built: the work of the Yahwist (J), of the\nElohist (E), and of the Deuteronomist (D). [For a brief introduction to these four sources, see the\nIntroduction to this commentary, \u201cLeviticus in Its Contexts,\u201d and for details, the Introduction to the\ncommentary on the book of Numbers.] If so, then Exod 32\u201334 belong mostly to the older composi-\ntions (JE), while chapters 25\u201331 and 35\u201340 belong to the Priestly level. The final editorial effort\nmay have had at least the following goal in mind: after the episode with the golden calf had\nbrought the newly formed community to the brink of destruction, it was thought necessary to have\na regularized and immediately available ritual for atonement. This could be provided by the erection\nof a portable sanctuary and by ordination of a perpetual priesthood\nThe motivation of the Priestly writers, in arranging the story as previously outlined, was more\nthan a historical reconstruction. To them, there were parallels between the apostasy at the sacred\nmountain at the time of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` (13th century BC) and apostasy in the sacred (\u201cpromised\u201d) land at\nthe time of the monarchy and beyond (10th century and downward). The former had been serious,\nbut the latter had been catastrophic: it had resulted in the exile to Babylonia (587\u2013539 BC). It was\nimperative, then, that the community, immediately upon its return from exile (beginning in 539 BC),\nrebuild the temple and resume ritual with scrupulous attention to detail and that it do so on the\npresumed model of an ancient tabernacle. The failures of the past must not be repeated and thus\ntragic history repeat itself. Rather, a community must now be created among whom God can\ndwell. \u201cI will meet with the Israelites there [in a properly constructed and administered sanctuary]\n[v_Exo_29_43] [v_Exo_29_44] [v_Exo_29_45] . . . and will be their God\u201d (Exod 29:43-45).\nThe text, then, plays on two levels: a historical retrospective in the wilderness period at the time\nof Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` (13th century), and a contemporary perspective of national restoration and temple recon-\nstruction at the time of Ezra and Nehemiah (i.e., at the time of P, in the 6th century).\nComposition\nThis narrative section may be divided into the\nfollowing sections for purposes of discussion:\n(1) The Installation of the Priests (8:1-36);\n(2) Implementation of the Cultic Service (9:1-24);\n(3) Challenges to Aaron `[char_Aaron_Exo_6]`\u2019s Authority (10:1-7).\n[v_Lev_8_1] Leviticus 8:1\u201310:20\nEzra reads Torah\nEzra reads the Torah to an assembly in Jerusalem after the return from exile in Babylonia.\nGustave Dor\u00e9. Ezra Reading the Law in the Hearing of the People from the Illustrated Bible. 19th C. Engraving. (Credit: Dover Pictorial Archives Series)\nmaking). This is the clear implication of the way that this section of\nLeviticus begins: \u201cThe LORD spoke to Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u201d (8:1), continuing\nwith \u201cMoses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` said to the congregation\u201d (8:5), \u201cAnd Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` took\u201d\n(8:10), \u201cHe then led forward\u201d (8:14), and so on.\nUltimately, then, knowledge of God and of the divine agenda is\nto come through the hearing, reading and proclamation of the\n\u201cWord\u201d and not through the performance of liturgical rites. The\nrites may be the primary locus where the sacred story is transmitted\nand may be important for communal identity and continuity, but\nthey are nonetheless secondary and dependent upon \u201cscripture.\u201d\nThis acknowledgement is of immense importance for determining\nultimate \u201cauthority\u201d in the modern Church and will be discussed\nbelow.\nThus the initial and primary religious event, once the exiles had\nreturned from captivity in Babylonia, was a community-wide gath-\nering to hear the reading of Scripture. We are told,\nAll the people gathered together . . . They told the scribe Ezra to\nbring the book of the law (torah) of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`, which the LORD had\ngiven to Israel. . . . And he read from it . . . from early morning until\nmidday . . . and all the people answered, \u201cAmen, Amen,\u201d lifting up\ntheir hands. Then they bowed their heads and worshiped the LORD\n[v_Neh_8_1] [v_Neh_8_2] [v_Neh_8_3] [v_Neh_8_4] [v_Neh_8_5] [v_Neh_8_6] with their faces to the ground. (Neh 8:1-6)\nThe scroll from which Ezra read on this occasion was likely the\nPentateuch in its final and present form, to which the Priestly writ-\nings (including Leviticus) had most recently been added.\nA modern commentator has put the point nicely:\nIn its essence, then, the early [post-exilic] Jewish community was a\nreligious group welded together through a variety of behavioral rules\ntransmitted in written form emerging from the recognition of the\none God Yahweh. That is, it was a confessional community, more a\n\u201ccitizen\u2013Bible\u2013community\u201d than a \u201ccitizen\u2013temple\u2013community.\u201d\nv. 8)\nD. Prohibitions and Consequences (vv. 9-21)\nC\u2019. \u201ckeep my statutes . . .\u201d (22-25)\nB\u2019. \u201c. . . be holy to me . . .\u201d (",
